Vertical Chart

# Function to create a bar plot with labels, dot as a thousand separator, and centered title
barplot_count <- function(dataframe, variable, title) {
  variable <- enquo(variable)
  
  df <- dataframe %>% group_by(!!variable) %>% summarize(count = n())
  total <- sum(df$count)
  df$percent <- df$count / total * 100  # Calculate relative percentage

  # Arrange the data frame in descending order of count
  df <- df %>% arrange(desc(count))

  # Randomly select one color from the specified list
  random_color <- sample(c('#4B5DA5', '#D486B8', '#67C1B5', '#6EA530', '#FADC08', '#E24232'), 1)

  # Create a bar plot with the randomly selected color
  p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = factor(!!variable, levels = .data[[quo_name(variable)]]), y = count)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "black", fill = random_color) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = "none",
          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +  # Center the title
    labs(title = title, x = quo_name(variable), y = "quantidade") +
    theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
          panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", fill = NA),
          plot.background = element_rect(fill = NA),
          legend.background = element_rect(fill = NA))

  # Add smaller labels to the columns with a dot as a thousand separator
  p <- p + geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("%s\n%.2f%%", comma(count), percent)),
                     position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 2)

  # Save the plot as a PNG file
  ggsave(paste0(title, "_ordered.png"), plot = p, device = "png", width = 8, height = 6, dpi = 300)

  # Print the plot
  print(p)
}

Horizontal Chart

# Function to create a horizontal bar plot with labels (count values), dot as a thousand separator, and centered title
barplot_count_horizontal <- function(dataframe, variable, title) {
  variable <- enquo(variable)
  
  df <- dataframe %>% group_by(!!variable) %>% summarize(count = n())
  total <- sum(df$count)

  # Randomly select one color from the specified list
  random_color <- sample(c('#4B5DA5', '#D486B8', '#67C1B5', '#6EA530', '#FADC08', '#E24232'), 1)

  # Create a horizontal bar plot with the randomly selected color
  p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = count, y = reorder(!!variable, count))) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "black", fill = random_color) +
    geom_text(aes(label = comma(count), x = count),
              position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 2, hjust = -0.2) +  # Adjust hjust for label position
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = "none",
          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +  # Center the title
    labs(title = title, x = "quantidade", y = quo_name(variable)) +
    theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
          axis.text.y = element_text(hjust = 0),
          panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", fill = NA),
          plot.background = element_rect(fill = NA),
          legend.background = element_rect(fill = NA))

  # Save the plot as a PNG file
  ggsave(paste0(title, "_horizontal.png"), plot = p, device = "png", width = 8, height = 6, dpi = 300)

  # Print the plot
  print(p)
}

Histogram

# Function to create a histogram with a random fill color
histogram_custom <- function(dataframe, variable, title) {
  # Randomly select one fill color
  random_fill_color <- sample(c('#4B5DA5', '#D486B8', '#67C1B5', '#6EA530', '#FADC08', '#E24232'), 1)
  
    # Filter out missing values and frequency less than 10
  dataframe <- dataframe %>%
    filter(!is.na(!!enquo(variable))) %>%
    group_by(!!enquo(variable)) %>%
    filter(n() >= 10)


  # Create a histogram with the randomly selected fill color
  ggplot(dataframe, aes(x = !!enquo(variable))) +
    geom_histogram(fill = random_fill_color, color = "black", alpha = 0.8, bins = 30) +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(title = title) +
    theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
          panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", fill = NA),
          plot.background = element_rect(fill = NA),
          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))  # Center the title
}

Incremental Variable

Analysis

As the chosen hypothesis, we decided to analyze the possibility of offering more products to those customers whose contracts involve 5 or fewer products. To proceed with the proposed analysis, a conditional variable was created that indicates whether the customer has more than 5 products in the contract or not.

# Create a new column 'multiplos_produtos' based on the condition
customers <- customers %>% mutate(multiplos_produtos = ifelse(Quantida_Produtos_Contrato > 5, 1, 0))
barplot_count(customers, multiplos_produtos, "Quantidade de Clientes por Múltiplos Produtos")

3) Relationship between variables

Analysis

Finally, to understand how the numerical variables relate to each other, some stacked graphs and boxplots were constructed for the variable under analysis (multiple products) and the variables that showed some level of correlation with it.

Stacked Bar function

# Function to create a stacked bar plot with labels
stacked_bar <- function(dataframe, X, Y, title) {
  colors <- c('#4B5DA5', '#D486B8', '#67C1B5', '#6EA530', '#FADC08', '#E24232')

  cross_tab <- table(dataframe[[Y]], dataframe[[X]])
  cross_tab_prop <- prop.table(cross_tab, margin = 1)

  df <- as.data.frame(cross_tab_prop)

  # Create a stacked bar plot
  p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = Var1, y = Freq, fill = Var2)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "black") +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(title = title, x = X, y = "Proportion") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("#414141", sample(colors, nlevels(df$Var2), replace = TRUE))) +  # Randomly assign colors
    theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
          panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", fill = NA),
          plot.background = element_rect(fill = NA),
          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),  # Center the title
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=0))  # Rotate x-axis labels


  # Add labels to the stacked bars
  p <- p + geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(Freq, accuracy = 0.01)), 
                     position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 2)

  # Print the plot
  print(p)
}

Boxplot

# Function to create a boxplot
boxplot_custom <- function(dataframe, X, Y, title) {
  # Select a color randomly from the list of acceptable colors for this type of plot
  colors <- c('#4B5DA5', '#D486B8', '#67C1B5', '#6EA530', '#4B5DA5', '#FADC08', '#E24232')
  
  # Create a boxplot using ggplot2
  p <- ggplot(dataframe, aes(x = !!sym(X), y = !!sym(Y), group = !!sym(X))) +
    geom_boxplot(fill = sample(c("#414141", colors), 1), color = "black", width = 0.5, outlier.shape = NA) +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(title = title, x = X, y = Y) +
    theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
          panel.border = element_rect(color = "black", fill = NA),
          plot.background = element_rect(fill = NA),
          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),  # Center the title
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 0, hjust = 0.5))  # Horizontal x-axis labels
  

  # Print the plot
  print(p)
}
